---
import RetroLayout from '../layouts/RetroLayout.astro'
import CrtMonitor from '../components/CrtMonitor.astro'
import BlinkText from '../components/BlinkText.astro'
---

<RetroLayout title="PixDock — Install Guide" activePage="install" description="Step-by-step installation guide for PixDock. One command to pixel paradise.">

  <section style="padding: 50px 0;">
    <div class="container">

      <h1 class="section-title section-title--green" style="font-size: 20px;">
        <span class="dim">// </span>INSTALLATION GUIDE
      </h1>

      <p class="text-center mb-5" style="color: var(--text-dim); max-width: 650px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
        Three ways to get PixDock running. Pick the one that matches your comfort level with terminals
        and existential dread about container orchestration.
      </p>

      <hr class="rainbow-hr">

      <!-- ═══ SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS ═══ -->
      <div class="bevel-panel mb-4">
        <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 12px; color: var(--neon-yellow); margin-bottom: 16px;">
          ⚙ SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS
        </h2>
        <table class="retro-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Requirement</th>
              <th>Minimum</th>
              <th>Recommended</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Docker Engine</td>
              <td>20.10+</td>
              <td>24.0+</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Docker API</td>
              <td>v1.41</td>
              <td>v1.43</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>OS</td>
              <td>Linux (amd64/arm64)</td>
              <td>Linux (any arch with Docker)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Memory</td>
              <td>64MB free</td>
              <td>128MB allocated</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Disk</td>
              <td>~50MB</td>
              <td>~100MB (with image layers)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Network</td>
              <td>Not required (air-gap OK)</td>
              <td>Internet for initial pull</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Browser</td>
              <td>Chrome/Firefox/Safari (modern)</td>
              <td>Any browser from this millennium</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ METHOD 1: ONE-LINER ═══ -->
      <div class="neon-box mb-4">
        <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 12px; color: var(--neon-green); margin-bottom: 16px;">
          METHOD 01: ONE-LINE INSTALL <BlinkText text="★ RECOMMENDED" />
        </h2>
        <p style="color: var(--text); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px;">
          The fastest way to get PixDock running. This script downloads the latest pre-built image from
          GitHub Container Registry, creates a Docker Compose file in <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">~/.pixdock/</code>,
          and starts the container. Done in about 15 seconds.
        </p>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash" style="margin-bottom: 16px;">
<span class="comment"># Default install — port 8420, no auth</span>
<span class="keyword">curl</span> <span class="flag">-fsSL</span> https://raw.githubusercontent.com/stormixus/pixdock/main/install.sh <span class="keyword">|</span> sh
        </div>

        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 9px; color: var(--neon-cyan); margin: 20px 0 12px;">
          ▸ OPTIONS
        </h3>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash" style="margin-bottom: 10px;">
<span class="comment"># Custom port</span>
<span class="keyword">curl</span> <span class="flag">-fsSL</span> ...install.sh <span class="keyword">|</span> sh <span class="flag">-s</span> <span class="flag">--</span> <span class="flag">--port</span> <span class="string">9000</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash" style="margin-bottom: 10px;">
<span class="comment"># With bearer token authentication</span>
<span class="keyword">curl</span> <span class="flag">-fsSL</span> ...install.sh <span class="keyword">|</span> sh <span class="flag">-s</span> <span class="flag">--</span> <span class="flag">--token</span> <span class="string">my-super-secret-token</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash" style="margin-bottom: 10px;">
<span class="comment"># Non-interactive (skip confirmation, useful for CI/automation)</span>
<span class="keyword">curl</span> <span class="flag">-fsSL</span> ...install.sh <span class="keyword">|</span> sh <span class="flag">-s</span> <span class="flag">--</span> <span class="flag">--yes</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash">
<span class="comment"># Uninstall — removes container, image, and ~/.pixdock/</span>
<span class="keyword">curl</span> <span class="flag">-fsSL</span> ...install.sh <span class="keyword">|</span> sh <span class="flag">-s</span> <span class="flag">--</span> <span class="flag">--uninstall</span>
        </div>

        <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 12px;">
          <strong>What the install script does:</strong><br>
          1. Checks that Docker is installed and running<br>
          2. Pulls <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">ghcr.io/stormixus/pixdock:latest</code><br>
          3. Creates <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">~/.pixdock/docker-compose.yml</code><br>
          4. Mounts <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">/var/run/docker.sock</code> into the container<br>
          5. Starts the service via <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">docker compose up -d</code><br>
          6. Prints the dashboard URL
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ METHOD 2: DOCKER COMPOSE ═══ -->
      <div class="neon-box neon-box--cyan mb-4">
        <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 12px; color: var(--neon-cyan); margin-bottom: 16px;">
          METHOD 02: DOCKER COMPOSE (BUILD FROM SOURCE)
        </h2>
        <p style="color: var(--text); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px;">
          Clone the repo and build from source. Good for development or if you want to customize
          the frontend before deploying.
        </p>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash" style="margin-bottom: 10px;">
<span class="comment"># Clone and build</span>
<span class="keyword">git</span> clone https://github.com/stormixus/pixdock.git
<span class="keyword">cd</span> pixdock
<span class="keyword">docker</span> compose up <span class="flag">--build</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash">
<span class="comment"># With authentication enabled</span>
<span class="keyword">PIXDOCK_TOKEN</span>=<span class="string">my-secret-token</span> <span class="keyword">docker</span> compose up <span class="flag">--build</span>
        </div>

        <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 16px;">
          The multi-stage Dockerfile handles everything: builds the Svelte frontend with Vite,
          compiles the Rust backend with Cargo, and packages it all into a tiny Alpine image.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ METHOD 3: SWARM ═══ -->
      <div class="neon-box neon-box--pink mb-4">
        <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 12px; color: var(--neon-pink); margin-bottom: 16px;">
          METHOD 03: DOCKER SWARM STACK
        </h2>
        <p style="color: var(--text); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px;">
          Deploy PixDock as a Swarm service. This is the recommended method if you're already running
          a Swarm cluster — PixDock will automatically detect Swarm mode and show the full cluster dashboard.
        </p>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash" style="margin-bottom: 10px;">
<span class="comment"># Build the image</span>
<span class="keyword">docker</span> build <span class="flag">-t</span> pixdock:latest <span class="string">.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash">
<span class="comment"># Deploy as a Swarm stack</span>
<span class="keyword">docker</span> stack deploy <span class="flag">-c</span> stack.yml pixdock
        </div>

        <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 16px;">
          The <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">stack.yml</code> includes placement constraints
          to run on manager nodes only (needed for Swarm API access), a 128MB memory limit, and
          automatic restart policy.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ METHOD 4: LOCAL DEV ═══ -->
      <div class="bevel-panel mb-4">
        <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 12px; color: var(--neon-purple); margin-bottom: 16px;">
          METHOD 04: LOCAL DEVELOPMENT
        </h2>
        <p style="color: var(--text); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px;">
          Run the backend and frontend separately with hot reload. Ideal for contributing or
          hacking on the UI.
        </p>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash" style="margin-bottom: 10px;">
<span class="comment"># Terminal 1 — Backend (Rust)</span>
<span class="keyword">cd</span> backend
<span class="keyword">cargo</span> run
        </div>

        <div class="code-block" data-lang="bash">
<span class="comment"># Terminal 2 — Frontend (Svelte + Vite, hot reload)</span>
<span class="keyword">cd</span> frontend
<span class="keyword">npm</span> install
<span class="keyword">npm</span> run dev
        </div>

        <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 16px;">
          The Vite dev server proxies API calls to the Rust backend automatically. Changes to
          <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">.svelte</code> files hot-reload instantly.
          Changes to <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">.rs</code> files require a
          <code style="color: var(--neon-green);">cargo run</code> restart (or use
          <code style="color: var(--neon-green);">cargo watch</code>).
        </p>
      </div>

      <hr class="rainbow-hr">

      <!-- ═══ TROUBLESHOOTING ═══ -->
      <div class="bevel-panel mb-4">
        <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 12px; color: var(--neon-red); margin-bottom: 16px;">
          🔧 TROUBLESHOOTING / FAQ
        </h2>

        <div class="bevel-inset mb-3">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 8px; color: var(--neon-yellow); margin-bottom: 8px;">
            Q: "I see 'permission denied' when accessing the Docker socket"
          </p>
          <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.6;">
            A: The container needs access to <code style="color: var(--neon-cyan);">/var/run/docker.sock</code>.
            Make sure your user is in the <code style="color: var(--neon-green);">docker</code> group,
            or run with appropriate permissions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bevel-inset mb-3">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 8px; color: var(--neon-yellow); margin-bottom: 8px;">
            Q: "The dashboard says 'Connecting...' but never loads"
          </p>
          <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.6;">
            A: Check that port 8420 (or your custom port) is not being blocked by a firewall. Also
            verify the container is actually running with <code style="color: var(--neon-green);">docker ps</code>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bevel-inset mb-3">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 8px; color: var(--neon-yellow); margin-bottom: 8px;">
            Q: "Can I run PixDock on macOS / Windows?"
          </p>
          <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.6;">
            A: Yes! As long as Docker Desktop is running, the Unix socket is available at the standard
            path and PixDock will work. On Windows with WSL2, it also works through the Docker Desktop
            integration.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bevel-inset mb-3">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 8px; color: var(--neon-yellow); margin-bottom: 8px;">
            Q: "Why port 8420?"
          </p>
          <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.6;">
            A: Because it looks cool, nobody else uses it, and port 80 was already taken. Science.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bevel-inset">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-pixel); font-size: 8px; color: var(--neon-yellow); margin-bottom: 8px;">
            Q: "Is this production-ready?"
          </p>
          <p style="color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.6;">
            A: PixDock is designed for monitoring dashboards — not mission-critical infrastructure.
            That said, the Rust backend is rock-solid, the memory footprint is tiny, and the auth
            system is sound. People are running it in production. You do you.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

</RetroLayout>
